# Error Handling

The App Router gives you three error-handling files: `error.tsx`, `global-error.tsx`, `not-found.tsx`. Each catches a different scope of failure. LLMs reliably get the scope rules wrong; this rule pins them down.

## `error.tsx` - route-segment error boundary

Catches errors thrown in the segment's `page.tsx` and everything below it. Must be a Client Component.

```typescript
// app/dashboard/error.tsx
'use client';

import { useEffect } from 'react';

export default function Error({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string };
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  useEffect(() => {
    // Log to observability platform
    console.error(error);
  }, [error]);

  return (
    <div role="alert" className="p-8">
      <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
      <p>{error.message}</p>
      <button onClick={() => reset()}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Key constraints:

- Must include `'use client'` - the boundary uses Client Component runtime.
- Receives `{ error, reset }` props. The `error` prop has a `digest` field with the server-side stack ID.
- The `reset()` callback re-renders the boundary's children.

## What `error.tsx` does and does NOT catch

This is the trap LLMs fall into. Draw the tree to keep it straight:

```
app/
  layout.tsx                  <-- root layout errors -> caught by global-error.tsx only
  error.tsx                   <-- catches root page.tsx + descendants
  global-error.tsx            <-- last-resort catch for anything that escapes every error.tsx
  page.tsx
  dashboard/
    layout.tsx                <-- this layout's THROWS -> caught by /app error.tsx OR global-error.tsx
                              <-- (NOT by /app/dashboard/error.tsx below)
    error.tsx                 <-- catches /app/dashboard/page.tsx + its children
    page.tsx
    settings/
      page.tsx                <-- a throw here bubbles up to /app/dashboard/error.tsx
```

The rule: `error.tsx` wraps its sibling `page.tsx` and the segment's children, but NOT the sibling `layout.tsx`. If you want to catch errors from a layout, the `error.tsx` must be ONE segment higher.

```typescript
// COMMON BUG - this layout's throw is NOT caught by the sibling error.tsx
// app/dashboard/layout.tsx
export default async function DashboardLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const data = await loadDashboardChrome();
  if (!data) throw new Error('Failed to load chrome'); // <-- escapes the sibling error.tsx
  return <div>{children}</div>;
}

// app/dashboard/error.tsx <-- this CANNOT catch the layout above
```

To handle a layout error, either:

1. Put an `error.tsx` one segment higher (`app/error.tsx`), or
2. Let it bubble to `global-error.tsx`, or
3. Handle the failure inside the layout itself (try/catch, render fallback content).

## `global-error.tsx`

The last-resort error boundary. Replaces the root layout when triggered, so it must render its own `<html><body>` tags.

```typescript
// app/global-error.tsx
'use client';

export default function GlobalError({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string };
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <html>
      <body>
        <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
        <p>An unexpected error occurred.</p>
        <button onClick={() => reset()}>Try again</button>
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}
```

Catches:

- Errors thrown by the root `layout.tsx`
- Errors thrown by `template.tsx`
- Anything that escapes every `error.tsx` in the tree

Without a `global-error.tsx`, top-level throws fall to the default platform error page (the Vercel "Application Error" page on Vercel, a generic 500 elsewhere). Every production app should have one.

## `not-found.tsx`

Rendered when:

- `notFound()` is called from a Server Component, Server Action, or Route Handler
- A route doesn't match any defined segment

```typescript
// app/not-found.tsx
import Link from 'next/link';

export default function NotFound() {
  return (
    <div className="p-8">
      <h2>404 - Not Found</h2>
      <p>The page you requested doesn't exist.</p>
      <Link href="/">Go home</Link>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Place at a specific segment for scoped 404s:

```
app/
  not-found.tsx              <-- catches unmatched routes app-wide
  blog/
    [slug]/
      not-found.tsx          <-- catches notFound() called inside this segment
      page.tsx
```

The nearest `not-found.tsx` ancestor renders.

## The `reset()` callback

`reset()` re-renders the error boundary's children. Useful for transient errors (network blips, a third-party API was down for 2 seconds). Useless for permanent errors.

```typescript
'use client';

export default function Error({ error, reset }: Props) {
  // For "Failed to fetch" - reset retries the fetch
  // For "User does not exist" - reset just shows the same error again

  return (
    <div role="alert">
      <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
      <p>{error.message}</p>
      <button onClick={() => reset()}>Try again</button>
      <a href="/">Go home</a>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Calling `reset()` does NOT clear the URL or any state outside the boundary. It just re-renders the children. If the error is a result of the URL (e.g. a missing record at `/posts/[id]`), reset will fail the same way. Use `redirect()` to a different URL for that case.

## `redirect()` and `notFound()` must be OUTSIDE try/catch

Both work by throwing a special error that the framework catches at the boundary. A `try { ... notFound(); ... } catch (e) {}` intercepts the throw and the not-found never triggers.

```typescript
// BAD - notFound swallowed
import { notFound } from 'next/navigation';

export default async function Page({ params }: Props) {
  const { id } = await params;
  try {
    const post = await db.post.findUnique({ where: { id } });
    if (!post) notFound(); // throws NEXT_NOT_FOUND
    return <Article post={post} />;
  } catch (e) {
    console.error(e); // logs NEXT_NOT_FOUND, then the function returns nothing
    return <div>Error</div>;
  }
}

// CORRECT - call notFound OUTSIDE try/catch
export default async function Page({ params }: Props) {
  const { id } = await params;

  let post;
  try {
    post = await db.post.findUnique({ where: { id } });
  } catch (e) {
    throw new Error('Failed to load post', { cause: e });
  }

  if (!post) notFound();
  return <Article post={post} />;
}
```

Same pattern for `redirect()`. See the `nextjs-server-actions` rule for the equivalent in actions.

If you must catch other errors and still allow `notFound` / `redirect` to propagate, re-throw any error whose message matches the framework signals (do NOT import the internal helpers - they live under `next/dist/*` and are not a stable API):

```typescript
try {
  // ...
} catch (e) {
  if (e instanceof Error && /^NEXT_(REDIRECT|NOT_FOUND)$/.test(e.message)) {
    throw e; // re-throw the framework signal
  }
  // handle other errors
}
```

## `redirect('/error')` vs `error.tsx`

Default to `error.tsx`. It is the canonical pattern: scoped, has access to the error object, supports `reset()`.

Use `redirect('/error')` only when the error context must persist across navigation (e.g. the user lands on a "your subscription is past due" page that has its own URL and lives across multiple sessions). Rare.

```typescript
// 95% of cases - use error.tsx, no redirect
'use client';
export default function Error({ error, reset }: Props) {
  return <div>...</div>;
}

// 5% of cases - the error has a stable URL surface
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation';

if (subscription.status === 'past_due') {
  redirect('/billing/past-due');
}
```

## Logging to your observability platform

Send the error to your observability platform from inside `error.tsx`. The `error.digest` field is the server-side stack ID - log it so the server-side trace can be correlated.

```typescript
'use client';

import { useEffect } from 'react';
import * as Sentry from '@sentry/nextjs';

export default function Error({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string };
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  useEffect(() => {
    Sentry.captureException(error, {
      tags: { digest: error.digest, boundary: 'dashboard/error.tsx' },
    });
  }, [error]);

  return (
    <div role="alert">
      <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
      <button onClick={() => reset()}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Sentry, GlitchTip (self-hosted Sentry-compatible), Datadog, Rollbar, Highlight - they all have Next.js integrations with the same shape. The integration usually instruments server-side automatically; the `error.tsx` `useEffect` is for the client-side surface of the error.

## Don't expose error details in production

`error.message` and `error.stack` may contain sensitive info (table names, internal IDs, infra paths). In production show a generic message; log the real one.

```typescript
'use client';

export default function Error({ error, reset }: Props) {
  return (
    <div role="alert">
      <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
      <p>
        {process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development'
          ? error.message
          : 'An unexpected error occurred. Our team has been notified.'}
      </p>
      <p className="text-xs text-zinc-500">Reference: {error.digest}</p>
      <button onClick={() => reset()}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The `digest` is safe to show users; it links to the server-side log without leaking the message.

## Common mistakes

- **`error.tsx` placed next to a `layout.tsx` expecting it to catch layout errors.** It cannot. Move `error.tsx` one segment higher, or rely on `global-error.tsx`.
- **`notFound()` inside try/catch.** Silently swallowed. Call outside the try/catch.
- **`redirect()` inside try/catch.** Same problem. Call outside, or re-throw any error whose message matches `^NEXT_(REDIRECT|NOT_FOUND)$` from within the catch.
- **Missing `'use client'` on `error.tsx`.** Next throws at build time with a clear message, but the trap is forgetting it on a copy-pasted file.
- **No `global-error.tsx`.** Root layout throws produce the default platform error page. Always ship one.
- **`global-error.tsx` without `<html><body>`.** It replaces the root layout, so it must render the document shell itself.
- **`reset()` button that calls `router.refresh()` instead.** Refresh re-fetches everything; `reset()` retries the boundary's children specifically. Different semantics.
- **Exposing `error.message` directly to users in production.** Leaks internal info. Show a generic message + the digest.
- **No `useEffect` to log the error.** Error happens, user sees the boundary, but nothing reaches your observability platform.
- **`not-found.tsx` only at the root when scoped 404s would be clearer.** Place `not-found.tsx` at the deepest segment that benefits from a tailored message.
- **Throwing strings instead of Errors.** `throw 'oops'` produces an error object with no stack. Always `throw new Error(message)`.
